Dealing with insignificant predictors

Finally, we need to decide between the remaining predictor variables. One way of understanding whether or not independent variables are colinear is whether there are disparities between the significance of the summary(lm) and the anova(lm). Highly colinear predictors may be significant in the anova but will both become insignificant in the linear model itself.

All of the variables are significant in the anova, but popn, poor are not in the lm summary. Lets see if we can figure out why.

Correlations

cor(nonw, poor)
## [1] 0.704915
cor(nonw, educ)
## [1] -0.2087739

Nonw is very correlated with both poor and educ. One of these three likely needs to be removed from the model in order for the others to become significant.

Lets try them all and see which one provides the best fit.

Testing which highly correlated variables (nonw, poor, educ) to remove

lm_nonw_rm <- lm(mort ~ jult + popn + educ +
              + poor + hc + so2)
lm_poor_rm <- lm(mort ~ jult + popn + educ +
             nonw + hc + so2)
lm_educ_rm <- lm(mort ~ jult + popn +
             nonw + poor + hc + so2)

AIC and Partial F-test of removed variables

Test which of the 3 correlated variables to remove based upon AIC and partial F-test. We would expect the variable to remove to increase the AIC and to not be significant in the partial F-test when added back in to the model.

This summary is quizzical. The anova shows that popn should be the most significant predictor of mort. However, it isnt significant in the model because its standard error is so high.

This is because popn is correlated with the other predictors in this model. It is likely that population itself doesnt affect mortality. Rather, factors that are correlated with population, like low education, higher summer temperatures, and lower white populations are affecting mortality.

Testing for interactions

Great, so with all the non-significant and colinear variables removed, were left with a model consisting of jult, educ, nonw, hc, and so2.

lm_final <- lm(mort ~ jult + educ + nonw + hc + so2)

As a last step, lets look for interactions. I do this the hard way.

lm_f_1 <- lm(mort ~ jult * educ + nonw + hc + so2)
lm_f_2 <- lm(mort ~ jult * nonw + educ + hc + so2)
lm_f_3 <- lm(mort ~ jult * hc +  educ + nonw+ so2)
lm_f_4 <- lm(mort ~ jult * so2 + educ + nonw)

lm_f_5 <- lm(mort ~ educ * nonw + jult + hc + so2)
lm_f_6 <- lm(mort ~ educ * hc + jult + nonw + so2)
lm_f_7 <- lm(mort ~ educ * so2 + jult + hc + nonw)

lm_f_8 <- lm(mort ~ nonw * hc + so2 + jult + educ)
lm_f_9 <- lm(mort ~ nonw * so2 + jult + educ + hc)

lm_f_10 <- lm(mort ~ hc * so2 + jult + educ + nonw)
AIC(lm_f_1, lm_f_2, lm_f_3, lm_f_4, lm_f_5, lm_f_6, lm_f_7, lm_f_8, lm_f_9, lm_f_10)
##         df      AIC
## lm_f_1   8 612.4162
## lm_f_2   8 612.0345
## lm_f_3   8 612.3879
## lm_f_4   7 617.1969
## lm_f_5   8 612.4877
## lm_f_6   8 612.5429
## lm_f_7   8 608.5356
## lm_f_8   8 612.4815
## lm_f_9   8 610.4248
## lm_f_10  8 608.7469

Models 7 (educ x so2) and 10 (hc x so2) both do well. We wouldnt expect being exposed to more SO2 would harm less educated populations more. We would, however, expect that being exposed to more of multiple air pollutants would increase mortality.

So, we remove model 7 from the choices and are left between lm_final (no interaction) and lm_10 (hc x so2)

Best model selection

An anova shows that, while p=0.07 and so it isnt statistically significant, including the interaction between hc and so2 in the model reduces the residual sum of square from 73,000 to 68,500. Because of this reduction, in combination with the lower AIC score, we choose the model with an interaction as the best model.

anova(lm_f_10, lm_final)

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
best_model <- lm(mort ~ hc * so2 + jult + educ + nonw)

Residual plot

Now that we have decided upon a best model for this data, lets make sure that the residual plot looks okay to make sure that our data is homoscedastic.

resid <- residuals(best_model)
yhat <- fitted(best_model)

residplot <- ggplot(data=pollution, aes(x=yhat, y=resid))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se = FALSE)+
  theme_bw()

print(residplot)

The residuals look good, the linear fit to the residuals is not sloped in either direction.

Fitted vs actual mortality

This graph shows the estimated mortality (yhat) calculated from the model coefficients and the observed (known) mortality. The model generally fits the data well except for at the very highest ranges of mortality.

yhatplot <- ggplot(data=pollution, aes(x=mort, y=yhat))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")+
  theme_bw()

print(yhatplot)
